    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Refers to the culture of the Arikara, an American Plains Indian people who lived along the Missouri River between the Cheyenne River in South Dakota and Fort Berthold in North Dakota. The Arikara, a Caddoan-speaking people, were culturally related to the Pawnee, from whom they broke away and moved gradually northward, becoming the northernmost Caddoan tribe. Wars and smallpox epidemics severely reduced their numbers by the 19th century. To escape further violence, the Arikara joined with the Hidatsa and Mandan tribes, known today as the "Three Affiliated Tribes."</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
